\section{Discussion}\label{sec:disc}
Here the sources of mechanical loads are briefly discussed at first.  That is followed by the effects of loads on the receptor potential and energy balance of an OHC.

\subsection{Elastic and viscous loads}\label{subsection:loads}
So far we proceeded without identifying the sources of the mass $m$, the external elastic load $K$, or the drag coefficient $\eta$. It is likely that the major part of the mass is external to the cell because an OHC is a small part of the organ of Corti, which moves with the basilar membrane on acoustic stimulation. The elements that can contribute to the external elastic load consist of the basilar membrane and local elastic elements in the organ of Corti. Contribution of these elements to the external load would depend on the mode of motion of this tissue and outside of the OHC. In the case of viscous drag $\eta$, the sources can be within the cell, the outer surface of the cell, or other cells and structures outside of the OHC. Voltage-dependent displacement of OHC requires movement of internal fluid, which may incur viscous drag. 

For obtaining an estimate of the internal drag, it would be reasonable to assume a cylindrical geometry for the OHC and the value $0.7$ kg/(m$\cdot$s) of water for the viscosity of the internal fluid.  The velocity the fluid is null in the middle and linearly increase towards the two ends, where it reaches $(1/2)an\cdot dP/dt$. A crude estimate could be obtained by using Poiseuille's law, which predicts the drag is $8\pi v\ell \times(\mathrm{viscosity})$, where $\ell$ is the length of the cylinder and $v$ the velocity of the fluid. If we can use the mean fluid velocity,  the resulting drag coefficient  is $\sim2\times10^{-10}$ kg/s, somewhat larger than the value $10^{-10}$ kg/s used for our low drag condition (Section \ref{subsubsection:small_eta}) and much smaller than $\eta_0\; (=10^{-6}$ kg/s) used elsewhere in the numerical examination.

This estimate, however, could still be an overestimate because the lateral membrane moves together with the fluid and unlikely to create a velocity gradient in the fluid as large as Poiseuille's law assumes. The internal drag could be less important than the drag on the outer surface, where the fluid motion can be more complex and should depend on the modes of motion of the whole tissue. In the following discussion, we assume that the major part of the drag $\eta$ is external, for simplicity.



\subsection{Receptor potential}
The numerical examination shows that the receptor potential is affected by an increase of elastic load and that of drag quite differently. While an increase in drag always increase the receptor potential (Fig.\ \ref{fig:drag_effect}A), an increase in the elastic load increases the receptor potential only slightly if drag is small (Fig.\ \ref{fig:small_eta}A) but it decreases the receptor potential if drag is larger (Fig.\ \ref{fig:large_eta}A). These observations suggest that drag is more effective than elastic load in enhancing the receptor potential that powers the cell's motility. 

\subsection{Amplifier gain}
The functional significance of OHCs as the cochlear amplifier depends on the balance between energy input and output. 
The energy required for stimulating the hair bundle consists of two components. One is elastic and the other is dissipative. The elastic component is recovered in the next cycle of stimulation during sustained oscillation. The work against viscous drag cannot be recovered. Therefore the balance of this energy has been considered critical for the sensitivity and sharp tuning of the ear \cite{g1948}. 

The present model allows an evaluation of OHC's output, which compensates for the dissipated energy for hair bundle stimulation. Examination of force or energy balance in the cochlea, however, cannot be made without a certain assumption on the mode of motion in the cochlea \cite{odi2003a,Ramamoorthy2012a}. 

In the following, input and output of energy are compared on cellular level. For this comparison, output values obtained under the condition $K\approx k$ and $\eta \approx 2 \eta_0$ are used so that the two kinds of outputs can be realized at the same time.

\subsection{Amplifier gain -- dissipative energy}
The dissipative energy required for input has been evaluated only for frog hair saccular bundles \cite{Bormuth2014}.  It is likely that the drag within the hair bundles of mammalian outer hair cells is much smaller than those of frogs.  Frog hair bundles are $\sim10 \mu$m tall, about 10 times taller than those of outer hair cells, and they are conical, consisting of tightly packed stereocilia of relatively similar lengths. Mammalian cochlear hair bundles consist of stair-like three rows of stereocilia with significantly different lengths. This morphological difference makes the gap area between stereocilia, in which shear is applied to the fluid during stimulation, much less in mammalian hair bundles than that in frog hair bundles. 

A crude estimation gives at least a 20-fold difference from this factor alone. In addition, stereocilia of mammalian hair bundles have larger root separations, further reducing internal drag. The tip displacement for full gating is $\sim$100 nm \cite{Bormuth2014} for frog hair bundles. A similar displacement is expected for mammalian hair bundles with uniform stimulation \cite{Nam2015}.

For these reasons, a frog hair bundle should have a friction coefficient much larger than the hair bundle of an OHC. Nonetheless, it could be used as an interesting reference point.
Full gating of frog hair bundle stimulated at 100 $\mu$m/s with amplitude $\sim$100 nm generates viscous force $\sim$20 pN \cite{Bormuth2014}. Thus energy dissipation is $10^{-19}$ J/half cycle for $f=500$ Hz for full gating. Thus 3\% gating corresponds to $3\times10^{-21}$ J/half cycle. If we extrapolate for higher frequencies, $2.4\times10^{-20}$ J/half cycle for frequency of 4 kHz. This value is smaller than $0.6$ aJ (or $6\times10^{-19}$ J)  by a factor 40 (See Fig.\ \ref{fig:drag_effect}B). Since frog hair bundles should have a much larger drag coefficient than mammalian ones, the the difference must be much larger. This discrepancy should allow OHCs to counteract drag generated elsewhere in the organ of Corti.

\subsection{Amplifier gain -- elastic energy}
Input and output of elastic energy are readily compared. The observed stiffness of the hair bundle of outer hair cells is between 1 to 3 mN/m~\cite{kenn-fet2005}. The hair bundle displacement required for 3 \% change in the bundle conductance (or resistance) is $\sim$0.03 nm \cite{kenn-fet2005}. Thus the energy required for changing the conductance by 3\% is $1.5$ aJ in the most efficient condition based on 1 mN/m bundle stiffness. The elastic energy output obtained from the model is $\sim0.2$ aJ at 4 kHz (Fig.\ \ref{fig:large_eta}B). It is 0.4 aJ even for small viscous drag (Fig.\ \ref{fig:small_eta}B).

It is possible that the experimental value could be somewhat overestimated. It is extremely difficult to stimulate a hair bundle  with an experimental probe as coherently as under physiological conditions~\cite{Nam2015}. If the gating of the channels in \emph{in vitro} settings is less coherent than in physiological conditions, the hair bundle sensitivity is less, requiring a larger displacement for achieving a given change in the conductance.  This leads to a larger elastic energy for stimulation because a larger displacement more than compensates a smaller stiffness as explained in the following.  

Consider that a hair bundle is an assembly of identical stereocilia pairs with a mechanotransducer channel between them. If an external force applied to the hair bundle is conveyed to stereocilia pairs evenly, the bundle stiffness is the sum of the pairs and the gating distance is the same as one of the pairs. The energy required to open all channels is the sum of energy required for moving the bundle along the distance to gate a single channel between every pair. If the external force is applied non-uniformly, the stiffness of the bundle as a whole is less than the sum of the pairs but the distance required for opening all channels is larger than that for a pair. That means a larger mechanical work because each pair with a given stiffness must be displaced more if the bundle is displaced non-uniformly.

Since elastic energy is conserved it is unnecessary for the output of an amplifier to match the input. Oscillation would be facilitated if the output partially compensates the input. Nonetheless it is interesting to notice that the order of magnitudes of input and output are close.

\section{Concluding remarks}
In this paper, a simple model for electromotility of OHCs is proposed to describe its behavior in a dynamic environment. The model is consistent with the experimental data so far obtained from isolated OHCs. The model also extends the expression for the membrane capacitance, incorporating the effects of frequency, drag, elastic load, and an associated mass. 

This model enables to describe the receptor potential and energy production by an OHC while its hair bundle is mechanically stimulated by sinusoidal waveform. It was found that the receptor potential is more significantly affected by the viscous drag than an elastic load.  The model predicts that the output of elastic energy is close to the input. However, the output of dissipative energy is much larger than input. These results are consistent with the biological role of the OHCs as an amplifier.

